AttributeValuesData.AttributeValue: White as is a tall forest tree with a straight, slender trunk, and a relatively small crown. It looks very much like the green ash (F. pennsylvanica), in fact, it is so hidden in the presence of green ash that it went essentially unnoted in Minnesota until 1966. It is largely restricted to mesic deciduous forests in the southeast and east-central counties. White ash are among the last trees to leaf out in the spring, usually after the flowers have appeared. White ash is a valuable timber tree. Its wood is commercially used for a variety of products including tool handles, oars, garden furniture and sports equipment. White ash is the wood used for Louisville Slugger baseball bats. White ash is threatened by the invasive emerald ash borer.
Ashy-gray to gray-brown, furrowed into close honeycombed or diamond-shaped areas separated by narrow interlacing ridges. On very old trees, slightly scaly along the ridges.
Purplish, early spring. Dioecious, usually unisexual.
1-2 1/2" long samara, narrowly obovate; wing extends from near base of broad, plump seed. Late summer-autumn.
Opposite, pinnately compound, 8-15" long, 5-9 leaflets, usually 7, stalked, 2-6" long, 1-3" wide, ovate to ovate-lanceolate.
Tall, slender trunked tree with relatively small crown. Honeycombed bark and opposite, pinnately compound leaves.
